{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_bindweed_ver02/data/sn83045774/00271744146/1921022001/0062.xml":{"full_text":"Automobile Forecast From Various Angles of Importance Show Business Outlook Good for 1921\nOUTLOOK FOR 1921\nGOOD, SAYS DEALER\nInteresting Forecast Considers\nBusiness From Various An\ngles of Importance.\ni\nBy WALTER A. WOODS,\njPresident of the Automobile Dealer 3\nAssociation.\nA forecast for 1921 is harder to make\nthan for any previous year, but there\nwill be Kvrf-i business for tootl cars in\nratio to the amount of prestige you have\nwith your customers, but we must have\nsound merchandising policy. Husineis\nIs going through a period of readjust\nment, and until a balance ia reached be\ntween prices that are asked for manu\nfactured products and the income re\nceived by actual producers we cannot ex\npect settled conditions. Farmers, 1 ivs\nStock raisers, miners, ike., are the only\nproducers of actual value and vu can\nSot obtain from them more than they re\nceive. These producers are now receiv\ning 80 per cent, less for their efforts\nthan they received a year ago, and to\n?how how far reaching tills Is 1 will\nquote from a competent authority who\n?ays that the combined income of the\npeople of this country in 1919 was sev- 1\nenty-five billion dollars, of which twentv- j\nfive billions was received by farmers, j\n*c.. and the other fifty billions by the j\nbalance.\nThe twenty-five billions of farm in-\ncome now totals not over fifteen billioiu,\nand most of that is tied* up in ware- 1\nhouses, for the farmer is reluctant to ac\ncept present prices; but eventually he j\nwill do so and this great volume of I\nmoney will bo turned into the channels\n?f business. When wheat was $2.75 a\nbushel a farmer could buy a hat costing\n$5.50 for two bushels of wheat; with\nwheat at $1.65 it will cost him three and\na half bushels. A suit of clothes that\ncould bo purchased for eighteen bushels\nof wheat now costs him thirty.\nThe farmer has refused to sell at\nprices olYered, has put his products In 1\nthe warehouse, cleaned his old hat and\nrepaired his old suit, and the manufac\nturer of these articles will do the same\nto his automobile until the value of farm\nlabor and manufacturing labor is more\nnearly equal.\nAll this commenced several months j\nago, and we passed the low mark iti I\nOctober, since which time there has been\na slow but sure improvement which\nshould reach its peak by April 1, and 1\nlook for exceedingly goOd business from\nnow on.\nAnother phase that we will go through'\nthis year will be the replacement of\ncars which have been discarded or,\neliminated. These figures show that evur\nelnce 1899 (twenty-two years) there has\nteen a steady and almost systematic in\ncrease in the production of automobiles,\nwith the single exception of 1918, when\nour factories were turning out imple\nments of war.\nAnother surprising fact is that the\nnumber of cars eliminated each year\nusually equals the production of the\nsixth previous year and is further em\nphasized by the fact that the production\nof the intervening'Ave yeara invariably\nis equivalent to the total registration of\nautomobiles in the United States. For\nInstance, the production of 1916, 1917,\n391S, 1919 and 1920 is equivalent to the\nregistration for 1920, and the pro\nduction for 1915, 1916, 1917, 1918 and\n1919 is equivalent to the registration\n/or 1919,\nIn view of the fact that these statis\ntics have held true for a period of\ntwenty-two years, during which time we\nnave passed through several panics and\na world war, it Is only reasonable to 1\nassume that predictions based on these\nstatistics will be fairly accurate.\nIf these figures hold true we can as- i\neume that In 1921 582.617 curs will be j\nneeded for replacement purposes, hut'\nowinj- to the fact that thu; will be the\nfirst year that replacement figures have\nexceeded the 1,000,000 mark. It will be\na very Interesting period for students of\nstatistics. I speak only for the New\nYork territory.\nFor 1921 I honestly expect that every\ndealer sellint; a product of merit can\nequal his 1920 business in the number i\nof cars delivered. Whether his Income\nIn the same depends upon his merchan\ndizing policy and his business policy.\nDealers should not carry too largo a\nstock of new cars on hand?a. two1\nmonths' supply should be the maximum\nat any time. Used car stock must be j\nmore rarcfulty watched this year than\never before, owing to the lsrsre nu?n-\nber of cara needed for replacement\nwhich will call for an increased volume\nof trading. Don't overload and don't\ntako in cars that are not in good run-\nning condition. It costs a lot of time\nand money to convert Junk Into cash\nand then you rarely get back what you I\nput Into it.\nBear In mind that prices of every- j\nthing aro receding and consequently'\nyour overhead and othor expense must\nalso come down. One year from to\nday your expenses should be at least\nSO per cent. le<?3 than w hat they are 1\nnow and the qulckor you get them\nthere the better.\nIn conclusion, T cannot help but tfuch\n?n the subject of service to the owner.\ndo not mean an intunKlble something\nthat the owner thinks he is going to\nget for nothing, but a definite policy\nof making sure that the owner gets\nwhat he pays for.\nA satisfied owner comes baSk for\nanother car and brings his friends with\nhim.\nDrive With Comfort\nSUMMER-WINTER\nRAIN-SHINE\nWith the\nCOPP\nSLIDE-SEDAN TOP\n(California Type)\nTop and llndv Work of\nKverjr Itesrrlptlon.\nFainting. I'phoNtertng, etc.\nGeorge W. Copp Co., Inc.\n!4tn St. Van Alst Ave.,\nLong Island City, N. Y.\nPhone Hunter* IN tnt .\"iH.io\nKAKIIKN ItlM KIIH t OI{4\nANCHOR TOPS COMES\nRebuilt Cars ij\nCerry New Car Guarantee I\nKxoelleiit opportunity to procur* I\nGwai ant?v?l rfcvrleas Klghta at\nS>Tl\nAll earn ftqunt to ntw,\n\\sn Ccrllandt Vehicle Corp.\nPeerless Distributor*\n1896 Broadway\nat 1-Id St.\nFhont Cot. ?7?J i\nI\nThen They Turn Around and\nBuild Him a Groat\nAutomobile.\n\"Where Is Marysville?\"\nThis has come to be a persistent ques\ntion in motoring circles everywhere?\ni und every \"circle\" is pretty much a\nmotoring circle nowadays.\nThe question naturally follows a state\nwent regarding the Wills Sainte Claire,\nthe new motor car Just placed in the\ni hands of dealers by C. H. Wills A Co..\nj the manufactures, whose factory and\noffices are at Marysville.\nMarysville is in Michigan, on the\nhanks of the St. Clair River between\nLake Huron and Lake St. Clair. It\nis two and one-half hours by trolley\nfrom Detroit and a few minutes' ride\ni from Port Huron. Sarnia, Ontario, la\nclose by on the other aide of tho watery\nboundary lino which divides tho Wol\nverine State from the Canadian\nprovince.\n\"Why, Marysville?\" Is the query\nwhich seldom fails to follow the answer\n'to the first question.\nO. Harold Wills, who between li?03\nand 1919 designed every model of\nmotor for the largest manufacturer of\nautomobiles in the world, decided to\nbuild a motor car, the details of which\nhad been taking shape gradually for j\nseveral years. It was to be, in the opin- j\nion of himself and his associates, not\njust another automobile, hut the best\ncar that could bo built at the price, a\ndifferent motor car, embodying new and\nstriking features of automoQve design\nand construction.\nTo carry out his ideas he east about\nfor a place In which to build?a place j\nwhich would present exceptional feat\nures?where land values were within j\nreason, where the soil and subsoil were\n?best adapted for building and where j\nfuture development would be assured.\nHe sought a place where workmen\nand their families might really llvo In\ncomfortable and attractive homes on\nsites largo enough to permit each fam\nily to have a garden; where spacious\nparks and boulevards and clean amuse\nment facilities could be had on a\nbroader scale than was possible in any\nother city.\nHe wanted a site where rail and water\ntransportation facilities were the best\npossible, both for incoming coal, steel\nand other manufacturing products, and\nfor outbound motor cars. But he also\nrequired a place convenient to tho great\nindustrial region of tho mid-West, within\neus.v reach of markets.\nMirysvlUe had already attracted the\nattention of Mr. Wills, when several,\nyears previous his yacht had anchored\nin the St. Clair River to await the end\nof a storm on Lake Huron. A later visit\nconfirmed his opinion of the location\nand revealed many desirable features\nwhich had not been apparent before.\nThe little village was then slumbering\npeacefully, the remnant of a past gen\nt-ration, \"the world forgetting, by the\nworld forgot.\" To-dny it has laid away\nthe shroud and winding sheet and\ndonned overalls, flannel shirts and put- j\ntees. It Is the centre of a thriving,\nhustling industrial city, for Mr. Wills\nand the men associated with him bought\nnot merely a factory site but more than j\n4,000 acres, and put the construction i\nmen at work to build a city which would\nbe u suitable home for the Wills Hair, to\nClaire c*r.\nEdwin B. Jacksog, well known a* a\nformer executive of the Packard and\nWillys-Overland companies, will have\ncharge of the New York sale* agency for\nthis care.\nBEST ROUTE TO PINEHUBST.\n1 lieeeut Survey Shown Travel Con\ndition* Art Good.\nTho main route to Plnehurat and\nSouthern Pines is now so much better\nthan usual at this time of year that\nas a result of a survey Just completed\nby A. C. Seller, one of its field men,\ntho American Automobile Association\nhas compiled a summary of present con\nditions.\nBy arranging the journey so as to J\nstop the fli'st night at Baltimore, Md.;\nthe second at Richmond, and the third\n1 at Clarksvllle, Va., tho trip may bo\nmade comfortably in lour days, aver-1\naging 157 miles a day.\nThe road to Baltimore, consisting en-\ntlrely of macadam and concrete, is in j\nexcellent condition. Motorists should be j\ncareful, however, to leave Philadelphia\nvia Baltimore avenue and follow the\nroute through Media, Ivennett Square\nand Cenowlngo, as the better known\nalternate via Wilmington and Havre do\nOrace is stilt quite rqugh in places.\nFrom Baltimore to a point about eigh\nteen miles below Washington excellent\nhard surfaced roads will be encoun-\ntered. Tho next twenty-one miles con- i\nslst of fair gravel, rough ir? spots, but j\nentirely passable. The notorious Chopa\nwamsic swamp section is now traversed j\nby a fine n> w concrete road three\nmiles in length, and its former terrors\nare eliminated. The balanco into Rich- I\nmond is mostly graded gravel, ex-\noept for a few short stretches just nortu\nof Fredcricksburg, which might cause\ntrouble in wet weather.\nLea vint; Richmond the motor traveller\nwill find excellent macadam and con\ncreto roada into Petersburg. A short\ndetour is probably still necessary Just\nbeyond this, and inquiry should accord\ningly be made before attempting it.\nThe rest of the route to Clarksville con\nsists of fair to good sand, clay and\ngravel, with occasional poor stretches,\nwhich slow down traffic temporarily.\nWhile the new bridge at Ooode's Ferry\nhas probably been finished, It Is not nd- i\nvisible to follow this route at present,\nowing to bad roads both north and\nsouth of that point. It would he better\nto continue on tho mam road into\nClarksville, and thence through to Pine\nhurst via Durham, thus making cer\ntain of roads which would l>e passable\noven in very wet weather. Under favor\nable weather conditions the route as a\nwhole is fairly good and should cause\nno particular difficulty or delay.\nWILL CELEBRATE INDIAN DAY.\nMoturcyolf Denlern CJet Together\nFeb. 23.\nIndian motorcycle dealers'all over the\nUnited States will observe Washington's\nBirthday, and also celebrate Indian day,\nas is customary at the same time.\nThis celebration has become a fixture\nIn thQ calendar of motorcycle events and\nlias been celebrated for the last ten\nyears.\nIndian day marks the opening of the\nnew spring riding season, and all motor\ncycle enthusiasts'will mnke themselves\nknown at the various agencies on the\n22d and have a general get together and\ngood time all day and evening.\nReliable Automobile Information\nREGARDING THE\nUsed Car Situation\nYou GAMBLE on the purchase of a used car ONLY when you j\nDO NOT BUY from a company uith an indisputable reputation\nfor fair deeding.\nYOU CAN BUY A TRULY RECONDITIONED CAR direct\nfrom a $100,000,000 Corporation?in business 67 years and doing\na $126,000,000 business euck year?for the Price of an Ordinary\nSecond-Hand Car.\nWe do NOT buy cars for cash, speculate in, or sell Used\nCars for a Profit.\nOur Rebuilt Car Department is conducted only as a convenience to\nthe new car buyer who is trilling to dispose of hw old car at the proper\ndepreciation rather than 6ell to the average Used ar Dealer, or dicker\nu ith a private party for a big price.\nAll used cars offered for sale by us therefore cost us Approximately\nwhat a Used Car Dealer pays cash, and his profit ue give to you by\nselling at a lower price, or putting the difference in honest repairs.\nOur Branch Factory and Service Station, the most complete of its\nkind in New York, enables us to recondition cars at a very small cost.\nThis is only one of the many reasons uhy we can offer you the excep\ntional values listed below:\nATOUR NEW YORK SALESROOMS\nSTUDEBAKKRS: Roconditioilt* Like New\n1920 Club Roadster, 4 passenger Light Six Cylinder.\n1920 Special Six touring, driven 4,137 miles.\n1910 Big Six touring, driven 2,100 miles.\n1919 Light Six touring, used very little.\n1919 Big Six touring, seven passenger.\nDODGE: 1919 touring, $775.00.\nOLDSMOBILE: 1920 four passenger Sport Model Speedster.\nAPPERSON: 1919 Chummy Roadster, $875.00.\nOAKLAND: 1920 Light Six touring, like new, $950.00.\nFORD COUPE: 1920 Model, used only three months.\nOAKLAND SEDAN: 1920 Model, four door, refinished.\nBUICK: $575 buys late 1917 Light Six touring.\nOVERLAND: 1920 touring, driven only 3,000 miles, $650.00.\nDORT: 1920 touring, driven only few miles, $875.00.\nELCAR: 1920 tour; exceptional condition, $875.00.\nAT OUR BROOKLYN SALESROOMS\nSTUDE BAKERS:\nLate model 5 and 7 passenger touring cars, reconditioned in our\nown shops. These cars look and run like new and furnish an\nopportunity for the used car buyer to get what is practically a\nnew car at a substantial reduction.\nCOLE: $715.00 buys 8 cylinder four passenger Sport model.\nLANDAU ROADSTER: 1917 9tudcbaker 6 cylinder, $400.00.\nCADILLAC: Late 8 cylinder 7 passenger touring.\nOLDSMOBILE: Late 1918 Sport model, $885.00.\nAll cars listed above may he inspected only at\nthe salesrooms designated, but may be purchased at\neither place.\nALL LATE STVDF.ltAKF.R MODELS ARE SOLD WITH OUR STAND\nARD STUDEBAKER FACTORY GUARANTEE.\nIf you w?uld get a BARGAIN, and the car of your choice?BUY NOW,\n>efore the Spring rush.\nOur present stock includes about 50 other cars of various makes nnd\nnodels, offering the best values In New York City.\nStudebaker Rebuilt Car Department\nBrooklyn Sale.sroom New York Salesroom\nledford Ave., Cor. Sterling PI. 1700 Broadway, Cor. 54th Street.\nOpen Evenings.\nLEGAL POINTS FOR\nAUTOMOBILE OWNER\nSome Novel and Informative\nPoints Recently Decided\nby the Courts.\nBy Ol R LEGAL CORRESPOWDEJIT\nIn preceding articles atantlon has\nbeen called to ths liability of a garage\novnnr for the loss of automobiles stored\nIn his garage and stolen therefrom. In\na recent decision of the Supreme Court\nof Minnesota the court extended this\nrule of liability to a ca.ce In which\nthere was a notice conspicuously posted\nIn the garage warning patrons that the\nowner would not be responsible for\ncars stolen from the premises. The\nevidence did not show that the partic\nular claimant in this case had seen the\nnotice, and the court exprenaly with\nheld decision on the question whether a\ncontrary ruling would have been made\nhad the tacts shown that the claimant\nwas aware of the notice In question.\nAs has been frequently pointed out\nIn this series, a violation of law on the\npart of a motorist does not nf Itself\nrender him liable for an accident which\noocurs whiila tho violation continues,\nthe rule being that there must be some\ndirect connection between such viola\ntion and the. accident complained of to\ncreate liability. In a recent Minnesota\ncase tho principle Is applied to a sit\nuation in which the motorist who w??\nviolating the law was the complaining\nparty. The claimant In this <*h.se had\nparked his machine within twenty feet\nof a fire hydrant, which was in viola\ntion of a local ordinance. While in\nthis position the oar was struck, by a\ncarelessly driven truck and crushed\nagainst th? hydrant In a suit against\nthe owner of the truck the latter con\ntended that the loss was due to the\nplaintiff's violation of law and that\nthis should defeat his claim. The court\ndid not, however, sustain this defence.\nIn several other recent cases decided\nJm the same State claims for damages\nto cars have been sustained although\nthe evidence showed that the machines\nwere not registered. As heretofore\npointed out in this series there la a\ndivergence of view on this question i>B\nthe part of the courts ef the varlaus\n8tat<*.\nPLANS FOR BROOKLYN SHOW.\nExhibit Will Include UtNl Mod\nels of LemlliiK Lines.\nAlthough it Is too e.irly to talk about\nthe lines that the l5rookl>n Motor Ve\nhicle Dealers Ass<>ciatlon are going to\nexhibit at Its tenth annuol show, which\nbegins at the Twenty-third Regiment\nArmory on Saturday, March 5, and lasts\na week, a tour through the heart of the\nmotorcar section of Brooklyn proves\nconclusively that th coming exhibition\nis going to be the greatest In the his\ntory of the organization.\nPractically all of the dealers have de\ncided upon the lines that they are going\nto exhibit. At the meeting last Wednes\nday nlsfht the committee showed Its floor\nplan, based upon the drawing on Feb\nruary 9. With one or two minor changes\nit was accepted and at once the dealers\nbegan to decide upon the type of car\nthat they are going to show.\nOf '-ouree, only the latest models will\nbe shown. From season to season the\nstyles in cars, particularly In town cars,\nchange quite as much as the gowns the\nsmart woman selects so carefully, not,\nperhaps, In g<neral outline every year,\nbut particularly in the little details of\ninterior decoration .so important to a\nI smart turnout. This year finds these\nchanges quite ns marked as In former\nseasons, and the mode in cars this year\nis greatly superior to that of last year.\nWOODS IIKADS DKALKKS' ASSOCIATION.\nAt a meeting of the board of directors of\nthe Automobile Dealers' Association Walter\nA. Woods was elected president; W. O.\nOrabtree, vice-president, and Albert Hirst,\nsicretary-tri-asurer.\nGeorge Booker has moved the Stearns\nKnlght branch Into larger quarters at lSiy\nH load way.\nV-W MMLI1WI 1'iwra?\nMOTOR TRUCKS\nGO over the Oakland\nSensible Six part by\npart. Throughout the car,\nas throughout the six\ncylinder, overhead-valve\nengine, every unit is es\nsential to higher efficiency,\ngreater service, longer\nlife. You pay for nothing\nsuperfluous when you buy\nan Oakland. No other\ncar equals its value at so\nmoderate a price.\n$200 to $700 Less\n600 vFewer Parts\nGreater Strength\nQUALITY and economy have brought Stewart suc\ncess. For Stewart Trucks built eight years ago\nare still working profitably for their owners; earning\ndaily satisfaction and paying dividends on the invest\nment.\nThey are sturdy trucks?designed right, built right, and\npriced right. The very first Stewarts made still serve the\nneeds of trade. Their first cost is $200 to 5700 less than\nthe average price of other trucks, and the saving con\ntinues throughout the trucks' long life ?on upkeep,\non repairs, tires, gasoline and oil.\nCapacities: 1, 1 '/2, 2, 2 and 3'/2 ton\nHerrman